I have gotten a functional matrix inverse for a matrix with consistent units.

      @units.wraps('=A**-1', ('=A'))
      def inv(a, *args, **kwargs):
          return numpy.linalg.inv(a, *args, **kwargs)

The return value appears to be correct. However, when I call it on a matrix with zeros, I get the following warning:

    C:\Users\{me}\AppData\Local\Continuum\Anaconda2\lib\site-packages\pint\quantity.py:855: RuntimeWarning: divide by zero encountered in reciprocal
      magnitude = new_self._magnitude ** _to_magnitude(other, self.force_ndarray)

Is this a bug? Or how should I avoid this?

Complete test code attached
[invtest.zip](https://github.com/hgrecco/pint/files/163644/invtest.zip)

Not sure if an issue but was hoping to get some insight as to how you might specify this spec. 
I have a dictionary that looks like this: 
`data = {"data": [{'name': 'bob',
                  'custom': {
                      'type': 'person',
                      'hobbies': [{
                          'biking': True, 'swimming': True
                      }]
                    }
                  },
                 {'name': 'joey',
                  'custom': {
                      'type': 'cat',
                      'hobbies': [{
                          'biking': False, 'swimming': False
                      }]
                    }
                  }]
        }`

and I want to get a dictionary that looks like: 
`{'names': ['bob', 'joey'], 'swims': [True, False]}`
the closest I'm able to get is by using this spec:  
`spec = {"names": ("data", ["name"]),
    "swims": ("data", ["custom"], ["hobbies"], [['swimming']])}`
but the 'swims' attribute comes back as `[[True], [False]]`
Is there a way to get those attributes out of those inner lists by adjusting the spec? It seems trivial but actually nested lists multiple levels deep seems pretty common in json.
BTW glom is super handy! 
Thanks, W

