Had a quick look over the c++ part of the implementation and noted that there is a lot of code like this in the library:

```c++
if (return_code == SQL_SUCCESS) {
        return output_handle;
} else {
        throw cpp_odbc::error(level2.get_diagnostic_record(input_handle));
}
```

The issue here is, that the driver or the driver manager decide to return SQL_SUCCESS_WITH_INFO the operation would fail. Since I discovered this issue purely by reading the code, I can not provide a specific combination of driver, driver manager and actions to produce an actual Bug. It still seemed worthy pointing out, though.

Consider https://groups.google.com/a/continuum.io/forum/#!searchin/anaconda/unittest2/anaconda/MWbKky9eU1s/W0JzFS1wKXIJ (this exact issue is no longer reproducible because I've deleted my unittest2 package). The issue there was that I had a unittest2=0.5.1=py26_0 package in my binstar that depended on distribute, but the one in Anaconda depends on setuptools. 

I'm not really sure what should be done about this. On the one hand, it could be blamed on the over specification of dependencies in Anaconda. Or perhaps we should extend the dependency specification to allow to specify that a package from a particular channel must be used. 

